-- Saudi, Qatar Shares Rise on Global Gain, Oil; Mobily Gains on Expansion
-- Dana El Baltaji
-- 2010-06-16T14:47:31Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-16/saudi-qatar-shares-rise-on-global-gain-oil-mobily-gains-on-expansion.html

          
          
             Saudi Arabian and Qatari shares
advanced as oil traded above $76 a barrel and global stocks
gained on optimism of a recovery in the U.S. economy.  
 Etihad Etisalat Co. , the Saudi Arabian phone company known
as Mobily, rose to the highest in more than six weeks after it
said it may spend more than 2.5 billion riyals ($670 million)
this year to expand.  Qatar Islamic Bank  gained 2.4 percent.
Saudi Arabia’s  Tadawul All Share Index  increased 0.4 percent to
6,346.44, the highest level since May 19. Qatar’s  QE Index 
advanced 0.7 percent to 7,029.21, rising a third time this week.  
 “The rise in European and U.S. markets has boosted Gulf
stocks,” said Shadi  Ramadan , trading manager at Al Dhafra
Financial Brokerage LLC in Abu Dhabi.  
 The  Bloomberg GCC 200 Index  climbed 0.6 percent. U.S.
stocks rallied yesterday after a report showing growth in New
York manufacturing boosted confidence that a recovery in the
world’s biggest economy will increase corporate earnings.
European  stocks  rose as much as 0.6 percent before reversing
gains today, the  MSCI Asia Pacific Index  climbed 1.1 percent and
the  MSCI World Index  advanced for a seventh day.  
 Crude for July delivery increased as much 0.3 percent to
$77.19 a barrel and traded at $76.80 a barrel on the New York
Mercantile Exchange at 5:52 p.m. Dubai time. The six nations of
the Gulf Cooperation Council, made up of the United Arab
Emirates, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman and Bahrain, supply
about a fifth of the world’s oil.  
 Mobily, Saudi Arabia’s second-largest mobile-phone company,
gained 2 percent to 51.50 riyals, the highest since May 2.
Capital expenditure as a percentage of “revenue will be the
same as what we did the previous year,” Chief Executive Officer
Khalid al-Kaf said in an interview today.  
 Qatar Islamic Bank, the Gulf state’s biggest Shariah-
compliant lender, climbed 2.4 percent, the most since May 10, to
73.9 riyals.  
 Abu Dhabi’s  ADX General Index  gained 0.3 percent while
Dubai’s  DFM General Index  retreated 1 percent to the lowest in
four months. Benchmark indexes in  Oman  and  Bahrain  fell 0.1
percent while Kuwait’s  gauge  advanced 0.2 percent.  
